The Py-GC–MS spectra of the PET and PET copolymer demonstrate the main thermal degradation process (Fig. 9
                           ) and their content change are presented in Table 6
                           . According to the chromatogram (Fig.S7), the main thermal degradation products of PET and PET copolymer have no noticeable change compared to neat PET, which indicates that the additions of CEPPA and gCDs did not transform the degradation mechanism of the PET matrix while changing the degree of degradation.

The mechanical properties can be expressed by three main parameters including tensile strength, elastic modulus, elongation (Fig. 12
                         and Table 7
                        ). In comparison with pure PET, the tensile strength of CEPPA-PET decreased 48.95 MPa from 50.46 MPa. The reason can be attributed to the regularity of PET molecular chain be broken. At the same time, the elastic modulus raises to 1157.80 MPa from 685.13 MPa, because the flexible segments of CEPPA absorb more energy when subjected to external forces. When the CEPPA and gCDs are added into PET matrix, the tensile strength increases by 9.21%, which indicates that gCDs promotes formation of crosslinked structures in the CEPPA-PET matrix. The elastic modulus value for CEPPA-gCDs-PET is higher 17.09% than CEPPA-PET, which reason can be attributed to that gCDs and PET form a s crosslinking structure and effectively transfer bearing stress [14]. Compared with PET, the elongation at break increases by 45.45%, the reasons can be attributed that the flexible chain segments in CEPPA are introduced into PET and the crosslinking structure inhibits the diffusion of microcracks. It is worth noting that when the gCDs is copolymerized into the CEPPA-PET, the tensile strength increases by 11.93% under the influence of gCDs.
